<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Sodium Sulfate" class="currentChild" href="Sodium_Sulfate">Sodium Sulfate</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A compound, whose formula is Na<sub>2</sub>SO4, that was for a time believed to be the substance responsible for the production of high quality wood <a title="Pulp" href="Pulp">pulp</a> in papermaking. Sodium sulfate was originally added to the older <a title="Soda Process" href="Soda_Process">soda process</a>, and a much stronger pulp resulted. (It has since been found, however, that the responsible chemical was actually <a title="Sodium Sulfide" href="Sodium_Sulfide">sodium sulfide</a>.) The pulping process has since been somewhat erroneously known as the <a title="Sulfate Process" href="Sulfate_Process">sulfate process</a>, although its alternate name, the <a title="Kraft" href="Kraft">kraft</a> process (after the German and Swedish word for "strength"), is perhaps more accurate. (See also <a title="Chemical Pulping" href="Chemical_Pulping">Chemical Pulping</a>.) 
</p>
